msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:163
msgid "**Tutorial**: :ref:`skipif`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:165
msgid "Skip a test function if a condition is ``True``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:170
msgid ""
"``True/False`` if the condition should be skipped or a :ref:`condition "
"string <string conditions>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:177
msgid "pytest.mark.usefixtures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:179
msgid "**Tutorial**: :ref:`usefixtures`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:181
msgid "Mark a test function as using the given fixture names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:185
msgid "The names of the fixture to use, as strings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:189
msgid ""
"When using `usefixtures` in hooks, it can only load fixtures when applied to "
"a test function before test setup (for example in the "
"`pytest_collection_modifyitems` hook)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:192
msgid "Also note that this mark has no effect when applied to **fixtures**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:199
msgid "pytest.mark.xfail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:201
msgid "**Tutorial**: :ref:`xfail`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:203
msgid "Marks a test function as *expected to fail*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:208
msgid ""
"Condition for marking the test function as xfail (``True/False`` or a :ref:"
"`condition string <string conditions>`). If a bool, you also have to specify "
"``reason`` (see :ref:`condition string <string conditions>`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:212
msgid "Reason why the test function is marked as xfail."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:214
msgid ""
"Exception subclass expected to be raised by the test function; other "
"exceptions will fail the test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:216
msgid ""
"If the test function should actually be executed. If ``False``, the function "
"will always xfail and will not be executed (useful if a function is "
"segfaulting)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:219
msgid ""
"* If ``False`` (the default) the function will be shown in the terminal "
"output as ``xfailed`` if it fails   and as ``xpass`` if it passes. In both "
"cases this will not cause the test suite to fail as a whole. This   is "
"particularly useful to mark *flaky* tests (tests that fail at random) to be "
"tackled later. * If ``True``, the function will be shown in the terminal "
"output as ``xfailed`` if it fails, but if it   unexpectedly passes then it "
"will **fail** the test suite. This is particularly useful to mark "
"functions   that are always failing and there should be a clear indication "
"if they unexpectedly start to pass (for example   a new release of a library "
"fixes a known bug)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:220
msgid ""
"If ``False`` (the default) the function will be shown in the terminal output "
"as ``xfailed`` if it fails and as ``xpass`` if it passes. In both cases this "
"will not cause the test suite to fail as a whole. This is particularly "
"useful to mark *flaky* tests (tests that fail at random) to be tackled later."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:223
msgid ""
"If ``True``, the function will be shown in the terminal output as "
"``xfailed`` if it fails, but if it unexpectedly passes then it will **fail** "
"the test suite. This is particularly useful to mark functions that are "
"always failing and there should be a clear indication if they unexpectedly "
"start to pass (for example a new release of a library fixes a known bug)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:230
msgid "Custom marks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:232
msgid ""
"Marks are created dynamically using the factory object ``pytest.mark`` and "
"applied as a decorator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:236
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.timeout(10, \"slow\", method=\"thread\")\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:242
msgid ""
"Will create and attach a :class:`Mark <_pytest.mark.structures.Mark>` object "
"to the collected :class:`Item <pytest.Item>`, which can then be accessed by "
"fixtures or hooks with :meth:`Node.iter_markers <_pytest.nodes.Node."
"iter_markers>`. The ``mark`` object will have the following attributes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:246
msgid ""
"mark.args == (10, \"slow\")\n"
"mark.kwargs == {\"method\": \"thread\"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:251
msgid "Example for using multiple custom markers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:253
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.timeout(10, \"slow\", method=\"thread\")\n"
"@pytest.mark.slow\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:260
msgid ""
"When :meth:`Node.iter_markers <_pytest.nodes.Node.iter_markers>` or :meth:"
"`Node.iter_markers <_pytest.nodes.Node.iter_markers_with_node>` is used with "
"multiple markers, the marker closest to the function will be iterated over "
"first. The above example will result in ``@pytest.mark.slow`` followed by "
"``@pytest.mark.timeout(...)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:265
msgid "Fixtures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:267
msgid "**Tutorial**: :ref:`fixture`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:269
msgid ""
"Fixtures are requested by test functions or other fixtures by declaring them "
"as argument names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:272
msgid "Example of a test requiring a fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:274
msgid ""
"def test_output(capsys):\n"
"    print(\"hello\")\n"
"    out, err = capsys.readouterr()\n"
"    assert out == \"hello\\n\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:282
msgid "Example of a fixture requiring another fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:284
msgid ""
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def db_session(tmpdir):\n"
"    fn = tmpdir / \"db.file\"\n"
"    return connect(str(fn))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:291
msgid "For more details, consult the full :ref:`fixtures docs <fixture>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/reference.rst:297
msgid "@pytest.fixture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:1
msgid "Decorator to mark a fixture factory function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:3
msgid ""
"This decorator can be used, with or without parameters, to define a fixture "
"function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:6
msgid ""
"The name of the fixture function can later be referenced to cause its "
"invocation ahead of running tests: test modules or classes can use the "
"``pytest.mark.usefixtures(fixturename)`` marker."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:10
msgid ""
"Test functions can directly use fixture names as input arguments in which "
"case the fixture instance returned from the fixture function will be "
"injected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:14
msgid ""
"Fixtures can provide their values to test functions using ``return`` or "
"``yield`` statements. When using ``yield`` the code block after the "
"``yield`` statement is executed as teardown code regardless of the test "
"outcome, and must yield exactly once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:19
msgid ""
"The scope for which this fixture is shared; one of ``\"function\"`` "
"(default), ``\"class\"``, ``\"module\"``, ``\"package\"`` or "
"``\"session\"``.  This parameter may also be a callable which receives "
"``(fixture_name, config)`` as parameters, and must return a ``str`` with one "
"of the values mentioned above.  See :ref:`dynamic scope` in the docs for "
"more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:20
msgid ""
"The scope for which this fixture is shared; one of ``\"function\"`` "
"(default), ``\"class\"``, ``\"module\"``, ``\"package\"`` or ``\"session\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:23
msgid ""
"This parameter may also be a callable which receives ``(fixture_name, "
"config)`` as parameters, and must return a ``str`` with one of the values "
"mentioned above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:26
msgid "See :ref:`dynamic scope` in the docs for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:28
msgid ""
"An optional list of parameters which will cause multiple invocations of the "
"fixture function and all of the tests using it. The current parameter is "
"available in ``request.param``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:33
msgid ""
"If True, the fixture func is activated for all tests that can see it. If "
"False (the default), an explicit reference is needed to activate the fixture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:38
msgid ""
"List of string ids each corresponding to the params so that they are part of "
"the test id. If no ids are provided they will be generated automatically "
"from the params."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/_pytest/fixtures.py:docstring
#: of _pytest.fixtures.fixture:43
msgid ""
"The name of the fixture. This defaults to the name of the decorated "
"function. If a fixture is used in the same module in which it is defined, "
"the function name of the fixture will be shadowed by the function arg that "
"requests the fixture; one way to resolve this is to name the decorated "
"function ``fixture_<fixturename>`` and then use ``@pytest."
"fixture(name='<fixturename>')``."
msgstr ""

